707-320:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Typically airline name or logo near front fuselage and/or tail; sometimes "707" series markings  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Horizontal color stripes or bands along fuselage, often on lower half; prominent airline liveries on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Narrow cylindrical fuselage, longer than early 707 variants  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-set swept wings with moderate dihedral, wingtip fuel tanks absent  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with slight point; cockpit windows in four-panel trapezoidal shape  
-Engine Number and Position: Four engines mounted in nacelles under wings, two on each wing  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer swept back; horizontal stabilizers mounted low on fin base, straight edges  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle gear; main gear retracts into wing roots or fuselage fairings, nose gear retracts forward  
-Window and Door Layout: Evenly spaced small rectangular passenger windows; multiple doors including forward and rear exits

727-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "727-200" often near rear fuselage or airline-specific text on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline liveries with prominent cheatlines or color bands along fuselage; tail often solid or with airline logo  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Tapered cylindrical fuselage, longer than 727-100, stretched mid-section  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted, swept wings with noticeable trailing edge flaps and spoilers  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with distinctive three-window cockpit arrangement (angled windshields)  
-Engine Number and Position: Three rear-mounted engines; two on sides of rear fuselage and one central in tail with S-duct intake  
-Tail Structure: T-tail configuration with high-mounted horizontal stabilizers on vertical fin  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle gear; main gear housed in fuselage with visible wheel wells below wings  
-Window and Door Layout: Uniformly spaced small rectangular windows; multiple main cabin doors including a rear airstair door beneath tail

737-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-200" markings near front fuselage or tail; airline-specific logos  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Narrow cheatline often present; airline liveries vary with bold stripes or solid colors  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Shorter, stubby cylindrical fuselage compared to newer 737 variants  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with slight dihedral; straight trailing edge with winglets absent  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone with angular cockpit windows arranged in a distinctive "eyebrow" formation (though some later 737-200 removed eyebrows)  
-Engine Number and Position: Two low-bypass turbojet engines mounted beneath wings, noticeably smaller and more cylindrical nacelles compared to later turbofans  
-Tail Structure: Conventional vertical stabilizer with rudder; horizontal stabilizers mounted low on fuselage  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main landing gear with distinctively long struts retracting into fuselage belly  
-Window and Door Layout: Small rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced; standard main entry doors near front and rear, possibly auxiliary overwing exits

737-300:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-300" usually near front or rear fuselage; airline-specific titles on tail or fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Varied airline liveries with distinct color bands along fuselage; logos on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Short to medium length fuselage; cylindrical with slightly tapered rear section  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with noticeable winglets absent (early 737 Classic variant)  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone; cockpit windows with angled inward slant and split eyebrow windows  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, close to fuselage with flattened bottom nacelle shape  
-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with single vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers mounted low on fuselage  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts into fairings under wings close to engine mounts  
-Window and Door Layout: Small, evenly spaced rectangular passenger windows; two forward and two rear service/exit doors on each side

737-400:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-400" text often near front or rear fuselage; airline-specific branding on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Typical 2-3 color airline liveries with bold stripes along fuselage; large airline logos on tailfin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Stretched fuselage compared to earlier 737 models; slightly wider cylindrical body  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with blended winglets (optional retrofit); noticeable wing trailing edge flaps  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone with distinctive 6-window cockpit layout, trapezoidal windows  
-Engine Number and Position: Two low-bypass turbofan engines mounted under wings, closer to fuselage than some competitors  
-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers, no ventral fins  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual main landing gear under wings/fuselage junction; nose gear forward under cockpit  
-Window and Door Layout: Multiple rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced; two over-wing exit doors per side in addition to front and rear main doors

737-500:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-500" sometimes near rear fuselage or engine cowling; airline-specific markings  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline liveries with horizontal cheatlines or color bands along fuselage; prominent airline logo on tail  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Shorter fuselage compared to other 737 Classic variants; cylindrical and moderately narrow  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with moderate sweep angle; winglets generally absent on original 737-500  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Distinctive pointed nose with slightly angular cockpit windows in a stepped trapezoidal layout  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, close to fuselage with flattened bottom nacelles (CFM56-3)  
-Tail Structure: Conventional vertical stabilizer with swept leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mid-level on tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle gear; main landing gear retracts inward into fuselage belly fairings  
-Window and Door Layout: Small, evenly spaced rectangular passenger windows; two main cabin doors on each side, with overwing exits consistent with 737 Classic series

737-600:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-600" badge near rear fuselage, airline-specific logos on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Classic Boeing narrow-body livery or airline color schemes concentrated around tail and fuselage midsection  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Shorter fuselage length than other 737 variants, narrow cylindrical body  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with blended winglets (optional)  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone, cockpit windows with five-panel trapezoidal shape  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, close to fuselage  
-Tail Structure: Tall, swept vertical stabilizer with standard horizontal stabilizers  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual main landing gear retracting inward under wings, noticeable nose gear under forward fuselage  
-Window and Door Layout: Standard small rectangular windows evenly spaced; two main passenger doors on each side, plus emergency exits over wings

737-700:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-700" often near rear fuselage or engine cowling
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline-specific liveries; curved cheatlines or swooping stripes common
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Narrow-body, short to medium length fuselage, slightly tapered rear section
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted, swept wings with blended winglets or split scimitar winglets
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, slightly pointed nose with signature 737 cockpit window arrangement (four main panels with angled edges)
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted beneath wings, close to fuselage
-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with tall vertical stabilizer; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid fuselage height
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual main landing gear retracting inward into fuselage; nose gear forward of wing root
-Window and Door Layout: Single row of evenly spaced rectangular passenger windows; two main passenger doors on each side plus emergency exits over wings

737-800:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-800" often near rear fuselage or engine; airline-specific text on tail or fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Distinct airline liveries; large tail fin logos; fuselage often solid or striped color schemes  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Narrow-body fuselage; length extended compared to earlier 737 models by approx. 5.4 meters  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with blended winglets (upturned tips)  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone; cockpit windows with characteristic sharp angular lower edge  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, closer to fuselage than some competitors  
-Tail Structure: Conventional single vertical stabilizer with horizontally aligned elevators  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts inward into fuselage fairings under wings  
-Window and Door Layout: Evenly spaced rectangular passenger windows; four main passenger doors on each side, plus two overwing emergency exits

737-900:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "737-900" often near rear fuselage or on engine nacelles
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Single or split color schemes with airline logos on tail and near front fuselage
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Extended fuselage length, longest variant of 737 Next Generation family
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with blended winglets common on newer models
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Slightly pointed nose with cockpit windows in sharp, angular trapezoidal layout
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted beneath wings, close to fuselage
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with swept leading edge, horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-fuselage tail cone
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts into fuselage and wing fairings
-Window and Door Layout: Passenger windows evenly spaced with additional overwing emergency exit doors; two main cabin doors on each side

747-100:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "747" or airline-specific logos prominently displayed near front fuselage and tail
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Classic livery with wide cheatline running along fuselage; airline emblems often on tailfin
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Distinctive wide-body fuselage with a noticeable upper deck hump extending from cockpit to mid-fuselage
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with noticeable leading-edge slats and trailing-edge flaps; four engines evenly spaced under wings
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with pronounced downward curvature under cockpit; distinctive extended upper deck with cockpit windows set forward
-Engine Number and Position: Four high-bypass turbofan engines mounted in pairs under each wing
-Tail Structure: Large vertical stabilizer with swept leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-fuselage near tail base
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Complex multi-wheel main landing gear assemblies visible under wings and fuselage; nose gear with dual wheels under cockpit
-Window and Door Layout: Passenger windows in two rows on lower fuselage plus smaller window row on upper deck hump; multiple front and rear passenger doors with overwing exits

747-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "747" or "747-200" often near front or rear fuselage; airline logos on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Distinct airline liveries with cheatline along fuselage; large, colorful tail logos  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Distinctive wide-body fuselage with pronounced hump upper deck extending halfway back  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Swept wings with noticeable dihedral; four podded engines mounted under wings  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, bulbous nose with iconic 4-window cockpit and extended upper deck hump  
-Engine Number and Position: Four engines, two mounted under each wing, in pods with circular inlets  
-Tail Structure: Tall, swept vertical stabilizer with horizontal stabilizers mounted low on tail cone  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Complex multi-wheel main landing gear with four bogies (two each side), visible when deployed  
-Window and Door Layout: Two rows of passenger windows — main deck single row, upper deck smaller windows above cockpit; multiple entry doors along fuselage

747-300:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "747-300" often near forward fuselage or rear section; airline-specific decals on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Classic 747 livery with extended upper deck paint line; airline logo prominent on vertical tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Extended upper deck fuselage, noticeably longer than 747-100/200; two-level passenger deck forward extending beyond the wing root  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with noticeable winglets (early variants may lack winglets)  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Distinctive "hump" upper deck nose with cockpit windows in the upper deck, rounded nose tip  
-Engine Number and Position: Four turbofan engines, two mounted on pylons under each wing  
-Tail Structure: Large vertical stabilizer with a swept leading edge and horizontal stabilizers low on tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Four main landing gear units — two under wings, two center gear under fuselage; visible multi-wheel bogies  
-Window and Door Layout: Two rows of passenger windows on upper deck extending over wing area; rectangular windows on main deck; multiple standard doors along fuselage including an extra door for the extended upper deck

747-400:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "747-400" often displayed near front or rear fuselage; airline-specific tail logos  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Distinct airline liveries; sweeping cheatlines; large airline logos on vertical stabilizer  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide, distinctive hump upper deck extending about 2/3 length of fuselage  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Swept wings with noticeable winglets angled upward at tips  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, bulbous nose with iconic cockpit windows forming a "flat eyebrow" pattern  
-Engine Number and Position: Four high-bypass turbofan engines mounted beneath wings, two per side  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with large aerodynamic rudder; horizontal stabilizers set low on tail assembly  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Four main landing gear sets (two under wings, two under fuselage center), plus nose gear; partially visible in retraction bays  
-Window and Door Layout: Upper deck windows in two rows along hump; standard rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced on lower deck; multiple large passenger doors along fuselage

757-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "757" often near rear fuselage or engine cowling; airline-specific decals on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Continuous paint schemes with full-length cheatlines; airline logos prominently on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Narrow-body fuselage, slightly elongated with a clean cylindrical profile, longer than 737 but shorter than 767  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-wing swept design with distinct winglets or raked wingtips on later models  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Pointed, elongated nose with sharply angled cockpit windows in a "wrap-around" style  
-Engine Number and Position: Two high-bypass turbofan engines mounted under wings, close to fuselage  
-Tail Structure: Tall, narrow vertical stabilizer with a straight leading edge and horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-fuselage  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual-wheel main landing gear retracting into body-side fairings; nose gear under cockpit area  
-Window and Door Layout: Single row of rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced; main entry door forward and service/exit doors near wing and rear

757-300:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "757-300" text often near rear fuselage or below cockpit; airline logos on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Commonly single color fuselage with airline-specific tail fin logos; sometimes stripes along fuselage length  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Very elongated narrow-body fuselage, longest variant in 757 family  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with blended winglets on many models  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Pointed nose cone; cockpit windows arranged in angular trapezoidal pattern typical of 757 series  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, close to fuselage  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with swept leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid to low tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts into fuselage fairings close to wing roots  
-Window and Door Layout: Multiple evenly spaced small rectangular passenger windows; four main passenger doors on each side including two emergency exits above wings

767-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "767" or specific airline model text near forward fuselage or engine nacelles  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Typically smooth color fades; large airline logos on tail and sometimes on engines  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body twin-aisle fuselage; relatively short length compared to other 767 variants  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted wings with moderate sweep; noticeable winglets may be present but not always  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, slightly pointed nose with six-pane cockpit windows; distinctive forward-slanting lower cockpit window  
-Engine Number and Position: Two high-bypass turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with slightly swept leading edge and horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear with two sets of four wheels each retracted into fuselage and wing fairings  
-Window and Door Layout: Two passenger doors and one overwing emergency exit per side; rectangular windows spaced evenly along fuselage

767-300:  
- Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Typically "767-300" or airline-specific model codes near front fuselage or rear  
- Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Distinctive airline liveries, often featuring sweeping curves or stripes along fuselage sides  
- Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body fuselage, longer than 767-200; slightly tapered rear section  
- Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with moderate winglets at tips  
- Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, blunt nose with slightly pointed tip; cockpit windows arranged in a six-pane layout with horizontal lines  
- Engine Number and Position: Two large turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side  
- Tail Structure: Tall, swept vertical stabilizer with horizontal stabilizers mounted near tail base  
- Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear housed in fuselage fairings, visible under wing roots  
- Window and Door Layout: Two rows of evenly spaced rectangular windows; multiple standard passenger doors near front, center, and rear

767-400:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "767-400" near front fuselage or rear above wings; airline logos on tail and fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Typical widebody airline liveries; often with sweeping stripes or color blocks along fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Extended fuselage length compared to earlier 767 variants; stretched narrow-body wide fuselage  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with raked wingtips extending rearward, longer span than 767-300  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with smooth contour; cockpit windows in swept-back trapezoidal style typical of Boeing  
-Engine Number and Position: Two high-bypass turbofan engines mounted under each wing, forward of landing gear  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with slightly swept trailing edge; horizontal stabilizers mid to low tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Main landing gear with four wheels per bogie, retracting into fuselage; nose gear single bogie under cockpit  
-Window and Door Layout: Multiple small, square-rectangle passenger windows in single deck row; extra door(s) on fuselage to accommodate longer body

777-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "777" or airline-specific model designation near front fuselage; airline logos on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Smooth, clean liveries; often swept or curved stripes; prominent airline logo on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body, cylindrical fuselage with slightly tapered tail section; medium length compared to other 777 variants  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Large, wide swept wings with raked wingtips angled sharply backward  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with slightly flattened lower contour; cockpit windows arranged in distinctive six-pane layout with angled central panes  
-Engine Number and Position: Two large turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per wing  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with slight sweep; standard horizontal stabilizers mounted low on tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual main landing gear bogies (6 wheels each) visible under fuselage; nose gear with two wheels at front  
-Window and Door Layout: Oval-cornered rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced; multiple large doors along fuselage including overwing emergency exits

777-300:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "777-300" often near forward or rear fuselage; airline logos on tail and fuselage
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Smooth livery with wide, often curved cheatlines or color bands; distinct airline-specific tail fin designs
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Very long, wide cylindrical fuselage with extended rear section; stretched compared to earlier 777 variants
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Large swept wings with raked wingtips; wings positioned low on fuselage
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with slightly pointed tip; cockpit windows in somewhat angular "eyebrow" pattern with no true eyebrow windows on newer models
-Engine Number and Position: Two large high-bypass turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side, with noticeable nacelle size
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with swept leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid to low tail section
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle gear visible; main landing gear with multiple wheels on each bogie, retracting into fuselage and wing fairings
-Window and Door Layout: Two passenger doors on each side at front and rear plus emergency exits mid cabin; oval-shaped windows evenly spaced along fuselage

A300B4:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Usually "A300B4" or Airbus logo near forward fuselage or tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Wide fuselage with colorful airline liveries, often with logo on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body, cylindrical fuselage with moderate length, slightly tapered rear  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted, swept-back wings with noticeable winglets (on later variants) or clean tips  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Blunt, rounded nose; cockpit windows arranged in a slight curve with characteristic Airbus window shapes  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side, relatively large nacelles  
-Tail Structure: Conventional vertical stabilizer with large horizontal stabilizers mounted low on tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle landing gear; main gear located under fuselage center, visible with multiple wheels  
-Window and Door Layout: Multiple small rectangular windows evenly spaced; main entry doors near front and over-wing emergency exits

A310:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A310" marking often near rear fuselage or tail; airline logos prominent
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Smooth, continuous airline liveries with curved lines; tail displays airline emblem
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body fuselage shorter and wider than A300; slightly tapered rear
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Mid-sized swept wings with noticeable winglets at tips
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with angled, multi-panel cockpit windows typical of Airbus
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side near fuselage
-Tail Structure: Conventional single vertical stabilizer with large, swept tailplane mounted mid-height
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual main landing gear under fuselage and wings; nose gear under cockpit
-Window and Door Layout: Evenly spaced rectangular passenger windows with slightly rounded corners; two main passenger doors each side near front and rear

A318:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A318" or Airbus logo near nose and tail sections  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Varied airline liveries; often prominent airline logo on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Short, wide-body fuselage; noticeably shorter than A319/A320 series  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted wings with moderate sweep; wingtip fences at ends  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with slightly tapered tip; cockpit windows curved with signature Airbus "eyebrow" panels  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side  
-Tail Structure: Conventional vertical stabilizer with horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle gear; main landing gear retract into rear fuselage fairings  
-Window and Door Layout: Single row of standard rectangular passenger windows; fewer doors than larger A320 family members

A319:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A319" markings near forward fuselage or on tail; airline-specific codes/logos
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline livery with clean, continuous color schemes; often tail logo prominently displayed
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Shorter, stubby fuselage compared to A320 family; cylindrical with slight taper at nose and tail
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with sharklets (upturned wingtips) on later models
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, slightly pointed nose with cockpit windows in tapered trapezoidal formation
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side
-Tail Structure: Conventional vertical stabilizer with horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-height on tail cone
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gears retract into fuselage belly, visible wheel wells under wings
-Window and Door Layout: Single row of small rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced; two main passenger doors on forward and rear fuselage, additional emergency exit doors over wings

A320:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A320" often near rear fuselage or on engine cowling; airline-specific text on tail and fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Typically clean, smooth fuselage paint; airline logos on tail and engines; sometimes cheatlines below windows  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Single-aisle, cylindrical fuselage with slightly tapered tail section; medium length for narrow-body  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted wings with noticeable wingtip fences (upturned vertical tips)  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone with distinctive cockpit window layout—six main windows with sharp angles (not trapezoidal)  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted below wings, one on each side  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with shape smoothly integrated into fuselage; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-height on tailcone  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle gear; main gears retract inward into fuselage; nose gear retracts rearward  
-Window and Door Layout: Single row of oval passenger windows evenly spaced; four main passenger doors (two forward, two rear), plus overwing emergency exits

A321:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A321" often near forward fuselage or rear door; airline-specific logos on tail and fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Single or dual color liveries with clean sections; airline logos prominently on tail and near cockpit  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Narrow-body with elongated, straight cylindrical fuselage longer than A320  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with sharklets (upturned wingtips) or blended winglets  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, aerodynamic nose with a slightly pointed tip; cockpit windows in a six-window trapezoidal pattern  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted beneath wings, close to fuselage  
-Tail Structure: Conventional vertical stabilizer with horizontal stabilizers mounted low on tail cone  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle gear; main landing gear retracts into fuselage fairings near wing roots  
-Window and Door Layout: Two main passenger doors per side plus overwing emergency exits; uniformly spaced oval cabin windows

A330-200:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A330-200" usually near forward fuselage or tail; airline-specific codes  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Clean fuselage with airline logos on tail and near front doors; often curved cheatlines or color blocks  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body, cylindrical fuselage; shorter than A330-300 variant  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted wings with moderate sweep; winglets with upward curve at tips  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with smoothly contoured cockpit windows; six main cockpit windows with characteristic “eyebrow” windows absent  
-Engine Number and Position: Two large turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side  
-Tail Structure: Tall, swept vertical stabilizer with small dorsal fin extension; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Dual main landing gear bogies under wings/fuselage fairings; nose gear visible under forward fuselage  
-Window and Door Layout: Two rows of evenly spaced oval passenger windows; typical four main passenger doors and smaller service doors

A330-300:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A330-300" typically near forward fuselage or rear; manufacturer logo near tail or nose  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline-specific liveries, often with curved or wave-like patterns along fuselage; large airline logo on tail fin  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body, cylindrical fuselage with relatively long length; smooth taper at tail section  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Wide, swept wings with noticeable winglets (curved upward tips)  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with smooth contour; cockpit windows arranged in slight upward curve with six main panes  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted under wings, one per side, large and rounded nacelles  
-Tail Structure: Conventional tall vertical stabilizer with slightly curved leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted low on tail cone  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gears retract into fuselage fairings under wings, visible wheel wells on underside  
-Window and Door Layout: Two rows of rectangular passenger windows; typically six or more entry/exit doors evenly spaced along fuselage

A340-200:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A340-200" often near front fuselage or on engine nacelles; airline-specific branding
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline liveries with smooth color transitions; logo typically on tail fin; minimal fuselage striping
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide-body fuselage, relatively shorter length compared to A340-300; smooth cylindrical profile
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted, swept wings with slight upward angle (dihedral); winglets absent or small depending on airline
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with a smooth, slightly pointed tip; cockpit windows in four-panel “eyebrow” layout absent
-Engine Number and Position: Four turbofan engines mounted under wings, two per side; spaced evenly and moderately sized
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with slightly swept leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid to lower tail section
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Nose gear under forward fuselage; main landing gears under wings and fuselage center; multiple wheels per gear for wide-body support
-Window and Door Layout: Two main passenger doors on each side; multiple small rectangular windows evenly spaced along fuselage; over-wing emergency exits present

A340-300:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): “A340-300” typically near rear fuselage or engine pylons; airline-specific text on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Wide-body airliner liveries; large airline logos on tail fins; often with consistent fuselage stripe  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Long, cylindrical fuselage with slight taper near tail; wide-body cross section  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with slight anhedral; winglets or sharklets present on later versions  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with smooth contour; cockpit windows with a distinct angular shape resembling a trapezoid but more rounded edges  
-Engine Number and Position: Four turbofan engines under wings, evenly spaced with two on each wing  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with swept leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted near base of vertical tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; four-wheel main bogies visible under fuselage below wings  
-Window and Door Layout: Multiple small oval or rectangular windows uniformly spaced; four main cabin doors on each side including over-wing exits

A340-500:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A340-500" usually near front fuselage or rear; airline logos on tail and fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline-specific liveries with clear logo on tail; often horizontal or diagonal stripes along fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Long, slender fuselage with minimal tapering near tail  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with slight curve at tips; noticeable winglets at ends  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with slightly pointed tip; cockpit windows arranged in a smooth, continuous line without deep angles  
-Engine Number and Position: Four turbofan engines under wings, two per side; spaced widely apart along wing  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with two horizontal stabilizers mounted midway up tail fin (T-tail is not present)  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear legs retract into fairings below wings and fuselage sides  
-Window and Door Layout: Evenly spaced rectangular passenger windows; multiple standard passenger doors along fuselage, including smaller service doors near nose and tail

A340-600:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "A340-600" or Airbus logo near front and tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Airline-specific liveries with large, continuous color bands or gradients along fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Very long and cylindrical fuselage, stretched beyond standard A340 variants  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted, swept wings with slight upward curve near tips; long wingspan  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose cone with signature Airbus cockpit window design featuring a sharp, angular six-window layout  
-Engine Number and Position: Four turbofan engines evenly spaced under wings, two per side, engines larger and more elongated than previous A340s  
-Tail Structure: Tall vertical stabilizer with slightly curved leading edge; horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-tail  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Multiple main landing gear sets, including a distinctive four-wheel center bogie under fuselage plus two main gear under wings  
-Window and Door Layout: Evenly spaced passenger windows in straight horizontal line; four main entry doors on each side including overwing exits

A380:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Usually large airline logo on tail, occasional "A380" or Airbus branding near front doors
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Two full decks with continuous paint schemes; large airline logos on tail and fuselage
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Double-deck wide-body fuselage with rounded, bulbous cross-section; notably tall and voluminous
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Very large swept wings with noticeable upward curve (winglets) at tips
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, bulbous nose with smooth, extensive cockpit window array spanning above upper deck
-Engine Number and Position: Four large turbofan engines, two mounted under each wing
-Tail Structure: Tall, wide vertical stabilizer with large rudder; horizontal stabilizers mounted high on tail cone
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Complex multi-wheel landing gear system, including four main landing gear groups spaced under fuselage and wing roots
-Window and Door Layout: Two full rows of passenger windows (upper and lower decks); multiple large doors distributed along fuselage for double-deck boarding

ATR-42:

-Fuselage Shape and Length: Short, thick cylindrical fuselage with slightly tapered rear

-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, bulbous nose with distinctive angular cockpit windows arranged in trapezoidal shape

-Tail Structure: T-tail configuration with horizontal stabilizer mounted atop vertical fin  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts into nacelles or fuselage  
-Window and Door Layout: Small rectangular passenger windows evenly spaced; single main entry door forward on left side; rear service door on some variants

ATR-72:

-Wing Configuration and Shape: High-mounted straight wings with noticeable winglets or slight upturn at tips

-Window and Door Layout: Few small rectangular windows along fuselage; large cargo doors on left side mid-fuselage and rear cargo ramp

BAE 146-200:

BAE 146-300:

BAE-125:

Beechcraft 1900:

C-130:

C-47:

CRJ-700:

Cessna 172:

-Wing Configuration and Shape: High-mounted straight wings with squared-off tips and slight dihedral
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with smooth cowling; large windshield with flat, multi-pane cockpit windows

-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with vertical stabilizer and horizontal elevators; rudder often with trim tab
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Fixed tricycle landing gear; main gear under wings/fuselage and nose gear under engine

Cessna 208:

-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with tall vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-fuselage
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Fixed tricycle landing gear with main gear legs visibly extended below fuselage and wing struts

Cessna 525:

-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted straight wings with slight sweep and winglets  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Pointed, narrow nose with wraparound cockpit windows forming a smooth curve  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted on rear fuselage, close to tail

Challenger 600:

DC-10:

DC-3:

PA-28:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): “Piper” or “PA-28” script near tail or below cockpit windows
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Simple stripes or accent lines running longitudinally along fuselage; no airline logos
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Single-engine, low-wing monoplane with relatively short and rounded fuselage
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted straight wings with tapered tips; no sweep
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with small spinner; clear canopy with side-by-side seating windows
-Engine Number and Position: Single piston engine mounted at nose
-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers in a T-style layout
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Fixed tricycle landing gear with wheel pants over main wheels
-Window and Door Layout: Two main side windows per side; one door on left side for entry

SR-20:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "SR-20" text near tail or rear fuselage; Cirrus logo on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Simple, clean paint schemes; often white with accent stripes along fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Short, tubular fuselage with slightly tapered rear  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-wing configuration; straight wings with slight taper and winglets on some variants  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with bubble canopy-style windshield; smoothly contoured cockpit area  
-Engine Number and Position: Single piston engine mounted in nose (tractor configuration)  
-Tail Structure: T-shaped tail with horizontal stabilizer mounted atop vertical stabilizer  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Fixed tricycle landing gear with wheel fairings on main gear  
-Window and Door Layout: Two side-by-side large rectangular windows per side; single entry door on left side behind wing

Saab 2000:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "Saab 2000" text near rear fuselage or tail; airline-specific logos on tail  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Simple, often two-tone paint schemes; distinct airline logos primarily on tail and near forward fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Long, slender cylindrical fuselage with slightly tapered rear  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted straight wings with slight taper and winglets at tips  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Pointed nose with sharply angled cockpit windows in trapezoidal pattern  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turboprop engines mounted under wings, one per side, with large six-bladed propellers  
-Tail Structure: T-tail configuration with horizontal stabilizer mounted atop vertical fin  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle gear; main landing gear retracts into nacelle fairings under wings  
-Window and Door Layout: Oval-shaped passenger windows evenly spaced along fuselage; front entry door forward of wing roots

Saab 340:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "Saab 340" text near rear fuselage or on engine nacelles; airline-specific tail codes  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Simple, often single or dual color schemes with airline logos on tail and forward fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Short, stubby fuselage with slightly tapered rear section  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: High-mounted straight wings with noticeable dihedral angle and squared-off wingtips  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded, slightly bulbous nose with large cockpit windows in a rectangular arrangement  
-Engine Number and Position: Two turboprop engines mounted on wings, one on each side, with prominent propellers  
-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with moderately tall vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers mounted mid-height  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts into engine nacelles or wing roots  
-Window and Door Layout: Oval passenger windows; a main passenger door near front on left side and smaller service doors near rear

Spitfire:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): RAF roundels and squadron codes; tail fin markings  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Camouflage patterns with disruptive green, brown, and grey tones; occasional invasion stripes  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Sleek, elliptical cross-section; relatively short and streamlined fuselage  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Elliptical wings with tapered tips; low-wing monoplane configuration  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Bubble or framed canopy with rearward taper; pointed nose with prominent spinner on propeller hub  
-Engine Number and Position: Single piston engine in nose driving a large, multi-blade propeller  
-Tail Structure: Conventional tail with rounded vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers mounted near base  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable main landing gear folding inward into wings; tailwheel under rear fuselage  
-Window and Door Layout: Single cockpit canopy; no passenger windows or doors; small access panels on fuselage sides

Tornado:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): "Tornado" or squadron/emblem markings on fuselage and tail fin
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Military camouflage patterns, often disruptive or low-visibility tones
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Broad, slightly flattened fuselage with variable geometry intake ramps on sides
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Variable-sweep wings, swept back in flight, straight or forward at low speeds
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Tandem two-seat cockpit with bubble canopy; sharp, pointed nose with radar radome
-Engine Number and Position: Two turbofan engines mounted side-by-side within fuselage rear section
-Tail Structure: Twin vertical stabilizers with slight outward cant; single horizontal tailplane
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Retractable tricycle landing gear; main gear housed in fuselage wing roots
-Window and Door Layout: Small cockpit canopy windows; absence of passenger windows; access via side cockpit/hatch doors

Tu-134:
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Cyrillic or numeric model designation, often near front fuselage or tail fin
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Thin cheatline stripe along fuselage; Soviet or Eastern Bloc airline liveries common
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Short, cylindrical fuselage with slightly tapered rear section
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted, swept wings with straight trailing edge and rounded tips
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: "Glass nose" with sharply pointed nose cone; cockpit windows arranged in angled trapezoidal pattern
-Engine Number and Position: Two rear-mounted turbojet engines flanking fuselage base
-Tail Structure: T-tail with large vertical stabilizer and horizontal stabilizers mounted high on fin
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear retract into wing roots close to fuselage
-Window and Door Layout: Oval passenger windows evenly spaced; single entry door near front on left side

Tu-154:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Cyrillic or Latin script markings, often near front fuselage or tail fin  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Bold horizontal cheatlines; commonly solid or dual-tone fuselage paint schemes; Soviet or Russian airline insignias  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Tapered cylindrical fuselage with rear fuselage narrowing notably toward tail  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Low-mounted swept wings with tapered tips; moderate sweep angle  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Distinctive pointed nose with sharply angled cockpit windows forming a slightly “eyebrow” effect  
-Engine Number and Position: Three rear-mounted engines; two on lower rear fuselage sides, one embedded in tail center with intake through tail base  
-Tail Structure: T-tail configuration with large vertical stabilizer and high-mounted horizontal stabilizers on top of fin  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gear retracts inward into fuselage, nose gear under cockpit  
-Window and Door Layout: Oval passenger windows evenly spaced; two or more front and rear entry doors including L1 and R1 near front fuselage

Yak-42:  
-Model Markings or Text (on fuselage or tail): Cyrillic or Latin "Як-42" or "Yak-42" near front fuselage; airline logos on tail or fuselage  
-Paint Patterns and Airline Logos: Solid or striped paint schemes; airline logos typically on tail fin and forward fuselage  
-Fuselage Shape and Length: Wide cylindrical fuselage with relatively short overall length compared to long-range airliners  
-Wing Configuration and Shape: Mid-mounted, straight swept wings with slight dihedral; noticeable winglets absent  
-Cockpit Shape and Nose Design: Rounded nose with slightly flattened bottom; cockpit windows in angular, wraparound style  
-Engine Number and Position: Three rear-mounted turbofan engines clustered at fuselage tail, two flanking sides, one centered at base of vertical stabilizer  
-Tail Structure: T-tail design with high-mounted horizontal stabilizer atop vertical fin  
-Landing Gear Visibility and Position: Tricycle landing gear; main gears retract into fuselage under wings; nose gear near cockpit  
-Window and Door Layout: Oval passenger windows evenly spaced along fuselage; single main entry door forward on left side
